CLASSICS_HL=Classics Tournament
CLASSICS_MAIN=<b>NOTE:</b><i class='small'>The below is how the tournament was played in 2006. Some smaller changes has been applied for this year's tournament, and some more may be applied. We will announce when the 2007 Classics Tournament system and rules are final.</i><br /><br />Yes! There will be a classics tournament at Stockholm Open! The Classics Tournament will be played on electromechanical and solid state machines from before 1985. <a href="http://www.spelautomatsamlarna.se/">The Swedish Game Machine Collectors Association</a> will be organizing the classics tournament.<br /><br />The Classics Tournament is open to anyone, both main tournament participants and other visitors of Stockholm Open. No preregistration is needed, you will be registered when you achieve your first highscore on any of the machines. There will be eight machines available to players, at the price of 5 SEK for a three balls game.<h3>Rules</h3>The basic rules of Stockholm Open main tournament will also apply to the Classics Tournament. However, it will not be based on the same scoring system as the main tournament. Instead, as the name implies, the goal is to beat the current highscore of the machine.<h4>Qualifications</h4>No prerequisites, except feeding a non-occupied machine with 5 SEK, is needed to begin playing. Highscore lists will be posted, with the top five scores for each machine. If you make it into the top five, please call for scorekeeper attention. Your score will be registered, and the highscore list will be updated.<br /><br />The player with the highest score on a machine is not allowed to play on that particular machine until his highscore has been overrun by a higher score.<h4>Advancing to the finals</h4>The players with the highest score on each machine will advance to the finals.<br /><br />If a player has the highest score on more than one machine, he will advance on the machine where he also has the second best score. If he has the second best score on none, or more than one, of the involved machines, he will advance on the machine where he has the third best score. This formula is extended to all five highscore list entries of the involved machines, as needed.<br /><br />If the formula is incapable of distinguishing between two or more machines (meaning that the number of second, third, fourth and fifth best scores achieved by the player on the involved machines are the same), a machine will be determined by means of drawing.<br /><br />The machine determined by these rules will be considered as the player's ticket to the finals.<br /><br />Out of the machines above, the players with the second best score on the machines NOT chosen as the above player's ticket to the finals, will advance to the finals, assuming that they haven't already qualified on another machine. If any player has more than one of these second best scores, the same rules as above apply on him too.<br /><br />If the player with the second best score has already qualified on another machine, the player with the third best score qualifies. Of course, this extends all the way down to the fifth best score. And of course, the formula above applies as usual. If the above formula is mathematically correct, and properly implemented, it should result in eight players qualified for the finals.<h4>Finals</h4>The finals will be played head on head on randomly drawn machines in a basic cup system, including a third prize match. Except for the cup system, the rules of the Stockholm Open main tournament applies to the Classic Tournament finals too.<br /><br /><b>Schedule</b><br />The qualifications will begin on Friday noon, April 6th. They will continue until Saturday evening 19.00. There are no limits to the number of qualification games played per player, except for the prohibition of playing a game where you already have achieved the current highscore. The finals will begin at Saturday 20.00, and will continue until last man standing!<h4>Pricing</h4>The games are coin-operated, and the price is 5 SEK for a three balls qualification game. The finals are free.<br /><br /><br /><a href="http://www.spelautomatsamlarna.se/"><img src="images/partners/sasf.gif" class='link' alt="The Swedish Game Machine Collectors Association" /><br /><img src="images/partners/sasf2.gif" class='link' alt="The Swedish Game Machine Collectors Association" /></a>

GENERAL_RULES_SPLIT_HL=Split Flipper Tournament specific qualification rules
GENERAL_RULES_SPLIT_MAIN=<i class="small"><b>NOTE: </b>This document may be changed without prior notice.</i><br /><br />All the <a href='rules.php'>general rules for the Stockholm Open</a> applies to the Split Flipper Tournament. And, these are the additional rules for the Split Flipper Tournament:<br /><br /><ul><li>The game has to be played by two players, using one flipper button/side of the machine each. The players are not allowed to change sides during a ball. However, in between the balls the players are allowed to change sides.</li><li>All modes etc. in the game has to be played by two players. Even the video modes.</li><li>Any kind of plunger, launch button (eg. NBA Basketball), gun (eg. Indiana Jones or Terminator 2) etc, can be controlled by any of the two players.</li><li>Any kind of button or other control located on the side of the machine (eg. Judge Dredd or Star Wars Episode 1), must only be controlled by the player on that side.</li></ul>

QUAL_DETAILS_HL=Details of the qualification system
QUAL_DETAILS_MAIN=<i class='small'><b>Note: </b>The general rules here applies to both the Main Tournament and the Split Flipper Tournament</i><br /><br />The qualification system at the Stockholm Open resembles the ones used at <a href='http://www.papa.org'>PAPA</a> and the <a href='http://www.flippersm.se'>Swedish Pinball Championships</a>.<h4>Entries</h4>Each player has {$g_iNoOfSweIncEntries} qualification entries included in the entrance fee (foreign residents have {$g_iNoOfForeignIncEntries} entries). Each qualification entry consists of three games on three different machines chosen by the player/team. The playing order is selected by the player/team, and players/teams will be assigned one of his or her chosen machines as soon as possible. When the game has finished, the player/team should stand waiting by the machine, until one of the scorekeepers is able to register the score. When all three games have been played, the player/team confirms that the scorekeeper has the correct scores, and the entry is registered into the computer systems. The player/team may now compile his or her next qualification entry.<h4>Additional entries, Main Tournament</h4>In addition to the {$g_iNoOfSweIncEntries} (or {$g_iNoOfForeignIncEntries}) entries included in the entrance fee, every player is entitled to buy a maximum of {$g_iAddEntriesSwe} (foreign residents: {$g_iAddEntriesForeign}) additional entries for {#MAIN_TOURNAMENT_ENTRY_PRICE_SEK#} ({#MAIN_TOURNAMENT_ENTRY_PRICE_EUR#}, {#MAIN_TOURNAMENT_ENTRY_PRICE_USD#}, {#MAIN_TOURNAMENT_ENTRY_PRICE_GBP#}) per entry.<h4>Additional entries, Split Flipper Tournament</h4>Every team is entitled to buy a maximum of {$g_iMaxEntries} entries for {#SPLIT_TOURNAMENT_ENTRANCE_PRICE_SEK#}  ({#SPLIT_TOURNAMENT_ENTRANCE_PRICE_EUR#}, {#SPLIT_TOURNAMENT_ENTRANCE_PRICE_USD#}, {#SPLIT_TOURNAMENT_ENTRANCE_PRICE_GBP#}) per player and entry. Note that the price is per player (i.e. not per team).<h4>Voiding entries</h4>A player/team may choose to void an entry at any time for any reason, as long as he or she hasn't yet confirmed the entry. As soon as the entry is confirmed, there's no way to void it. Voiding an entry still requires the entry fee be paid.<h4>Voiding teams</h4>A split flipper team may choose to void the entire team, making it possible for the players to form new teams. Voiding a team also effectively voids any entries played by the team. These entries will be disregarded in the qualification system.<br /><br />Any given player may be a member of one active team only. To form another team, the player's current team has to be voided first. To void a team, both players must inform the information desk about the decision. Certain circumstances (sickness, no-show, hangover) may in exceptional cases allow only one player to void a team.<br /><br />Voiding a team is final and can not be undone. However, the same players can form the same team again, but this will not result in any additional entries above the maximum of {$g_iMaxEntries} per team, the old entries played before the void will still be voided, and the team will have to pay a new entrance fee. In short, this is not a very bright idea. Forming a new team with another player will entitle this new team to buy {$g_iMaxEntries} new entries.<h4>Scoring</h4> When entered into the computer, the entries will receive points according to how good the scores on each individual machine are. The best score on each machine will receive {$iTopScore} points, and the scores below will receive a decreasing amount of scores. A table of the points received for each place can be found <a href="qualPoints.php">here</a>. During the tournament, live standings will be dynamically calculated and published on the Internet and on big screens on site. However, these standings are preliminary, and the final standings will, due to the nature of the system, not be available until all qualification rounds of the entire tournament (Main or Split Flipper) have been entered into the system.<h3>Finals, Main Tournament</h3>The {$g_iNoOfPlayersInFinals} best players, receiving the most points, will participate in the <a href='finalsDetails.php'>finals</a>.<h3>Finals, Split Flipper Tournament</h3>The {$g_iNoOfTeamsInFinals} best teams, receiving the most points, will participate in the <a href='finalsDetails.php'>finals</a>.

FINALS_DETAILS_HL=Finals
FINALS_DETAILS_MAIN=<h3>Main Tournament</h3>The {$g_iNoOfPlayersInFinals} best players after the qualification rounds have finished will advance to the finals. If several players end up on the same number of points, their second best (and then third best, etc) qualification entries will be compared to determine their place in the system. If, after comparing all their entries, they still end up on the same number of points, they will draw lots about their places.<br /><br />This year, it's a straightforward cup ladder beginning with the 1/16-finals, but the eight best players will step into the ladder in the 1/8-finals. This means only players placing 17 to 24 will play in the 1/16-finals, and the winners will meet the eight best players in the 1/8-finals. All matches are head-to-head in best out of three games. The matches will be played on three random drawn machines. The players will be advancing in a traditional cup manner, except for the eight best players waiting for the second run. At the gallows end, only two players will remain, and they will battle for the glorious victory.<br /><br /><i class='small'>The two players losing the semifinals will play one game on a random drawn machine to win the third prize. The final will begin after this 3rd prize match.<br /><br /><b>Note:</b> Depending on the number of participating players, we might need to revise the number of players going to the finals. If so, the system will still be the same, but the number of players entering the ladder in different phases might change. No changes will be made after the qualifications has begun.</i><br /><br />For a graphical and easy to understand view of the system, click on the picture below.<br /><br /><a href="images/misc/cup_2007.gif"><img src="images/misc/cup_2007.small.gif" alt="Cup System of the Finals" class='link' /></a><h3>Split Flipper Tournament</h3>The {$g_iNoOfTeamsInFinals} best teams in the <a href='qualDetails.php'>qualifications</a> will advance to the finals. Each stage of the finals will be played in a straightforward head to head cup system (best out of three matches), starting with {$g_iNoOfTeamsInFinals} teams in the quarter finals. There will be a 3rd place match before the final begins.<br /><br />For a graphical and easy to understand view of the system, click on the picture below and maximize the window popping up.<br /><br /><a href="images/misc/so-finals-split.gif"><img src='images/misc/so-finals-split.small.gif' alt="Cup System of the Split Flipper Finals" width="360" class='link' /></a>

LOCATION_HL=Location
LOCATION_MAIN=The tournament will take place at the <a href='http://www.kth.se/'>Royal Institute of Technology, KTH</a> in Stockholm. The actual building hosting the tournament can be found <a href="http://www.ths.kth.se/karhuset/index.html">here</a> (in Swedish). KTH is located in the northeastern part of central Stockholm, called "Östermalm".<br /><br /><table width='454'><tr><td valign='top'><img src='images/misc/nymble_ext.gif' alt='KTH' /><br /><i class='small'>KTH</i></td><td><a href="images/misc/nymble2.gif" ><img src='images/misc/nymble_small.gif' class='link' alt='Nymble'/></a><br /><span class='small'>A map over the tournament area (<a href="images/misc/nymble.gif">Full size image</a>).</span></td></tr></table><h3>How to get there</h3><h4>By subway (Tunnelbanan)</h4>The easiest way to get there is by subway. Get on the northbound T14 red line destined for "Mörby Centrum", and get off at the "Tekniska Högskolan" subway station. The ride takes 6 minutes from the central station "T-Centralen". Subway stations are marked by round signs with a big "T".<h4>By bus</h4>The bus lines 4 (towards "Radiohuset"), 43 (towards "Ruddammen"), 44 (towards "Skansen" or "Ruddammen"), 72 (towards "Frihamnen") and 73 (towards "Ropsten") all stop at KTH, at stops labelled "Tekniska Högskolan" or "Östra station".<h4>By taxi or foot</h4>The address of the KTH locality where the tournament will take place is Drottning Kristinas väg 19. From the subway station or bus stops on Valhallavägen, it is a 50-meter northbound walk. We will put up signs pointing out the way to walk. From the main (north) city center and the central train station, it is approximately 20-30 minutes to walk. From the south city centre, add another 20 minutes.<br /><br /><a href='http://www.sl.se/english/'>SL</a> is the operator of most public transportation in Stockholm. <a href='http://www.taxistockholm.se/'>Taxi Stockholm</a> is the biggest taxi operator, and you can order a taxi directly on their web site.<h3>Maps</h3><table><tr><td valign='top'><b>Subway</b><br /><img src='images/misc/tbana.gif' alt='Subway' /><br /><span class='small'>Click <a href='http://reseplanerare.sl.se/en_default.htm'>here</a> to show how to get to the location by public transportation. Type your current station/bus stop/address and then "Tekniska Högskolan" as destination.</span></td><td valign='top'><b>Detailed Map</b><br /><img src='images/misc/map.gif' alt='Subway' /><br /><span class='small'>Click <a href='http://kartor.eniro.se/query?&amp;what=map_adr&amp;mop=aq&amp;searchInMap=2&amp;mapstate=5%3B18.072463%3B59.346209%3Bs%3B17.972448%3B59.378365%3B18.172410%3B59.314135%3B1041%3B631&amp;mapcomp=%3B%3B%3BValhallav%E4gen%3B79%3B%3B11427%3BSTOCKHOLM%3B%3B%3B%3B%3B18.072463449075403%3B59.34620867195822%3B0%3B0%3B%3BSTOCKHOLM%3Bmaps_address.1094757.11%3B0&amp;geo_area=Valhallav%E4gen%2079&amp;stq=0&amp;pis=0'>here</a> to go to an interactive map of Stockholm. (Swedish text, but you'll figure it out)</span></td></tr></table><h3>Facilities</h3>There is a bar, a small convenience store and internet capabilities on site. Down at the subway station, there are several other restaurants, bars, convenience stores and an Internet café.<br /><br />

TRAVEL_HL=Travel
TRAVEL_MAIN=Stockholm is the capital of and the biggest city in Sweden. As such, is is the main hub of transportation in the country. I.e., it is easy coming here, whether by air, sea, train, bus, car or canoe. <h3>Air</h3> There are two international airports in Stockholm. Arlanda is the biggest, and it is located about 60 km north of the city. There is a high-speed train ("<a href='http://www.arlandaexpress.com/'>Arlandabanan</a>") going to the city. It costs 190 SEK, and takes about 20 minutes. There are also not so fast, but cheaper, buses from <a href='http://www.flygbussarna.se/'>Flygbussarna</a> going the same way. They cost 90 SEK. A taxi takes about 30-40 minutes and costs about 400 SEK.<br /><br />The other international airport, Bromma, is located much closer to the city center, and a taxi to the center would take about 10-15 minutes and cost about 150-200 SEK. Also, <a href="http://www.flygbussarna.se/">Flygbussarna</a> have buses going from Bromma to the city center. Bromma is a quite small airport, and only short-distance flights from northern Europe arrives here.<br /><br />Low-cost airlines have flights arriving at Västerås and Skavsta airports. These airports are more than 100 km away from Stockholm, but you can travel to Stockholm with the <a href="http://www.sj.se/">SJ</a> trains or <a href="http://www.flygbussarna.se/">Flygbussarna</a> buses.<h3>Sea</h3>If you're coming from the east (Finland, Balticum, Russia etc), the easiest and most comfortable way to get here is to travel on one of the party ferries crossing the Baltic Sea. There are ferries going to Stockholm from Turkku, Helsinki, Tallin, Riga, Klaipeda and St. Petersburg. Ferry operators include <a href="http://www.birkacruises.com/">Birka Cruises</a>, <a href="http://www.vikingline.fi/">Viking Line</a>, <a href="http://www.tallink.fi/">Tallink</a> and <a href="http://www.silja.com/">Silja Line</a>.<h3>Bus</h3>There are buses in regular traffic from most cities in Sweden and from major cities in the surrounding countries. Bus operators include <a href="http://www.swebusexpress.se/">Swebus Express</a>, <a href="http://www.safflebussen.se/">Säfflebussen</a> (in Swedish or German) and <a href="http://www.eurolines-travel.com/">Eurolines</a>.<h3>Train</h3>There are trains going to Stockholm from all major cities in Europe. Check out <a href="http://www.sj.se/">SJ</a> or your favourite train operator.<h3>Car</h3>The European highways E4, E18 and E20 goes through Stockholm.<h3>Canoe</h3>Follow the Golf Stream.<h3>Map</h3><a href="images/misc/location.GIF">Here</a> is a magnifying map guiding you all the way! More maps are available <a href="location.php">here</a>.

ACCOMODATIONS_HL=Accommodations
ACCOMODATIONS_MAIN=<h3>Hotel</h3>We will announce a great offer from a good hotel soon, but if you want to book your accommodations already now, you can use this <a href="http://www.hotellsverige.se/">hotel guide</a> or this <a href="http://www.stfturist.se/templates/MapSearch.aspx?id=5095">youth hostel directory</a>.<h3>On a tight budget?</h3>If you are a poor student, or by some other reason have a tight budget, you can always try contacting us <a href="contact.php">here</a>, and we will try to find a kind host among the Stockholm pinball-community for you.

PAY_SUCCESS_HL=Payment Successful
PAY_SUCCESS_MAIN=Your payment seems to have been successful. A soon as we can confirm that the money has arrived to one of our accounts, we will mark your registration as paid, and you will be guaranteed participation in the tournament. This may take an hour, or it may take several days. If your name hasn't been marked as "Paid" in a couple of days, please <a href="contact.php">contact us</a>.

PAY_CANCEL_HL=Payment Cancelled
PAY_CANCEL_MAIN=By reasons beyond our knowledge, you cancelled the payment, or some error occurred. Please <a href="entranceFee.php">try again</a>.

RESULTS_2004=<h2>Results 2004</h2><br /><b>March 30th, 2004</b><br />Stockholms Öppna Mästerskap (The Stockholm Open Championships)<br /><br />On Saturday, February 28th 2004, the tournament Stockholms Öppna Mästerskap took place at Lasergame. The crème de la crème of Sweden's pinball players all attended with the mission to once and for all settle who was the ultimate champion, as well as battle for the 1st prize, a No Fear pinball machine! The pinball machines used for the tournament were mostly the same as were used for the previous evening's party, i.e. Totan, TAF, AFM, SS, IJ, I500, TZ, Dr Who, DM, CV, ToM, and WCS. All of them were set on tournament mode, without extra balls.<br /><br />The 44 players were seeded into six groups where they met each other twice. From each group, the two best players advanced to the quarterfinals. The winners of the quarterfinals advanced to the semifinals, and finally there was a grand battle for the 1st prize among the last four players. A few unexpected events from the quarterfinals: the pinball queen from Gävle, Helena (YOO) Walter, lost after failing to charm Dr Who. Svante (SVE) Ericsson managed to send Jorian (JOE) Engelbrektsson packing, even though he's attended Pinburgh with honor, but Jorian lost on Totan no less. Another fan favourite, Karl (KGB) Broström, who came in at 4th place at PAPA '98, was defeated in the quarterfinals in spite of all his super jackpots on IJ.<br /><br /><b>The scores in the semi finals:</b><br /><br /><b>Group N (semi), games CV, TZ and TAF<br /></b>Victor TFF Håkansson: 2 3 0, total 5p, 3rd place<br />Patrik PAL Bodin: 3 1 1, total 5p, 2nd place<br />Linus S P Jorenbo: 0 0 2, total 2p, 4th place<br />Mats MCR Runsten: 1 2 3, total 6p, 1st place<br /><br />In group N, TFF started off strongly and set the pace, while both S P and MCR at first got left behind in the dust. But then MCR managed to Tour the Mansion on TAF on the first ball, and upped the ante for the rest of the players. TFF failed to crawl his way back up to the top and finally ended up third.<br /><br /><br /><b>Group M (semi), games TOM, AFM and SS<br /></b>Per "APB" Holknekt: 3 1 1, total 5p, 3rd place<br />Stellan "S B" Bliomqvist: 1 0 0, total 1p, 4th place<br />Stefan "FEZ" Andersson: 2 3 2, total 7p, 1st place<br />Fredrik "F L" Lindberg: 0 2 3, total 5p, 2nd place<br /><br />The first player in Group M, Per APB Holknekt, were also #1 on ToM. The reigning Swedish Champion, Stellan "Dr Flipper" Blomqvist, was just a pale shadow of his usual self, while Stefan FEZ Andersson played like a machine. The audience fully expected a hair-raising shoot out on SS, but all the players "choked" simultaneously, and APB missed the opportunity to advance to the finals due to a failed crate shot in the duel against Fredrik L.<br /><br /><br />The battle in the finals for the 1st prize went down between Fredrik (F L) Lindberg, Mats (MCR) Runsten, Patrik (PAL) Bodin and Stefan (FEZ) Andersson and the games were Cirqus Voltaire, Attack from Mars and Twilight Zone. The players received points based on their scores, with the winner getting 3 points, and whoever ends up in last place received 0 points. It was close to midnight and the day was starting to take its toll on the remaining combatants.<br /><br /><br /><b>Results:<br /></b><br /><b>Cirqus Voltaire Score and Total<br /></b>1st Mats Runsten 3 3<br />2nd Fredrik Lindberg 2 2<br />3rd Stefan Andersson 1 1<br />4th Patrik Bodin 0 0<br /><br />The winning score was just 80M.<br /><br /><br /><b>Attack from Mars Score and Total<br /></b>1st Fredrik Lindberg 3 5<br />2nd Mats Runsten 2 5<br />3rd Stefan Andersson 1 2<br />4th Patrik Bodin 0 0<br /><br />Everybody had a mediocre start but Fredrik took a firm lead starting with his second ball, after scoring more than 20B on his first (!) Total Annihilation. MCR tried to catch up with his third ball but had to settle for 2nd place with a score of 28B. This wasn't enough to threaten Fredrik, who ended up with 45B.<br /><br /><br /><b>Twilight Zone Score and Total<br /></b>1st Fredrik Lindberg 3 8<br />2nd Stefan Andersson 2 4<br />3rd Mats Runsten 1 6<br />4th Patrik Bodin 0 0<br /><br />Fredrik had a sweet set up for the final game as it was only MCR who could challenge him for the 1st place, and only on the condition that he won and Fredrik ended up as #3 or less. But Fredrik nailed it with a LITZ on the first ball. MCR, usually on good terms with TZ, was cursed with a bad road map and failed to find anything but bumpers, and that sealed the deal.<br /><br /><br /><b>The winners were:<br /></b>1st Fredrik Lindberg<br />2nd Mats Runsten<br />3rd Stefan Andersson<br />4th Patrik Bodin<br /><br />Fredrik won a No Fear pinball machine and Mats a Game Boy Advance including Pokemon Pinball. Stefan and Patrik were handsomely rewarded with LOTR translites and a selection of other Stern products.
